    {
      "id": "custom-1777559791410",
      "title": "Office Safety",
      "reference": "DAFMAN 91-203 paragraph 2.5",
      "trainingRequirement": "Document the local task or hazard, identify where the training is located, and explain how completion is documented.",
      "trainingSource": "Custom module",
      "notes": "Common office safety hazards include slips, trips, and falls from wet floors or cables, and ergonomic injuries from improper workstation setups. Other hazards involve improper equipment use, falling objects, electrical hazards, lifting heavy objects overhead and could include environmental factors like poor air quality. Common injuries include strains, cuts, and bruises. Slips, Trips, and Falls are the most common office injury usually from wet floors, loose rugs, electrical cords crossing walkways, and broken stairs.  Slips, trips, and falls also occur outside the office in parking lots not properly maintained or from snow and ice.  Ergonomic hazards occur from poorly adjusted chairs, keyboards, or monitors causing musculoskeletal disorders (back pain, carpal tunnel). Physical or object hazards can occur from Improperly stacked files falling, open desk drawers, or lifting heavy objects incorrectly.  Electrical hazards exist from frayed cords, overloaded power strips, and daisy-chained extension cords, which pose fire risks. Improper use of paper cutters, sharp scissors, or malfunctioning chair wheels has cause reportable injury to AFRS members. Environmental hazards are caused by poor ventilation, lack of fresh air, dust, or mold, which can lead to illnesses.",
      "link": ""
    }
